To terminate a C program, you can use the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. Here's an example code snippet:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    exit(0);
    return 0;
}
```

In this code, we include the `stdlib.h` library which provides the `exit()` function. The `exit()` function takes an integer argument as the exit status. In this case, we pass `0` to indicate a successful program termination.

By calling `exit(0)`, the program will terminate immediately and none of the subsequent code will be executed. The `return 0;` statement is not reached in this example, but it is a common practice to include it to indicate a successful program execution.

Remember to always include the necessary header files (`stdio.h` and `stdlib.h` in this case) for the functions you use in your program.

